# Security

## Secrets

- Never commit API keys, tokens, passwords, or private keys. Use environment variables or the host’s secret mechanism; document required vars in `.env.example` without real values.
- Never ship server-only secrets to client bundles. Treat anything in frontend code as public.

## Input and output

- Validate and sanitize on the **server** for every trust boundary (API routes, webhooks, file uploads). Client validation is UX only.
- Use parameterized queries / the ORM/driver correctly; never build SQL with string concatenation from user input.
- Encode or escape output by context (HTML, URLs, JSON) when rendering user-controlled data.

## Authentication and authorization

- Prefer established managed auth (Supabase Auth, Firebase Auth, Auth0, Clerk, etc.) over custom password/session/crypto.
- Every sensitive action must check **authorization** (who is allowed), not only authentication (who they are). Do not trust role or user id from the client alone.

## Architecture

- Before implementing, flag risky patterns: trusting client-only checks, missing authz on admin/mutation routes, logging tokens or PII, overly broad CORS, security by obscurity, or storing secrets in code or public config.

## When security conflicts with speed

- Default to the safer approach; briefly note the tradeoff (latency, complexity) so maintainers can decide.
